They are reconstruction engines.

You might say:

Knowledge stores facts.

Languages store reconstruction procedures.

The repo appears to be evolving toward the latter.

The test, of course, is whether future readers can successfully rehydrate the intended pattern from the compressed form.

If they can, then the pattern survived.

If they can’t, then the compression became too lossy.

That actually fits your “Golden Thread” idea quite well:

The thread is not the words.

The thread is what can be reconstructed from the words.

And every time a future reader successfully reconstructs the pattern, the thread effectively passes through another mind.

Not unchanged, perhaps.

But still recognizable.